Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome to our 23rd Weekly Dose of Optimism. It=E2=80=99s =
our Jordan edition. Let=E2=80=99s make it the greatest of all-time (at leas=
t, up to this point.)=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Composer [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/c7433fc5-6336-4bc3-ad80-b531360344af?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
You know Composer, I love Composer =E2=80=94 the investing app that helps y=
ou achieve superior returns with logic and data. Since founding its algorit=
hmic trading platform in 2020, Composer has helped over 20,000 customers tr=
ade=C2=A0100s of millions of dollars. I=E2=80=99m one of them =E2=80=94 aft=
er finally admitting I=E2=80=99m a terrible trader, I=E2=80=99ve moved my p=
ublic markets investing to Composer=E2=80=99s automated strategies and I tr=
y to add to my account whenever I can.
Here=E2=80=99s what I like about using Composer:=20
The product combines beauty and power =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s my favorite in=
vesting UX
Automation, rebalancing, and conditional rules mean I can take emotion out =
of it
I can copy smarter peoples=E2=80=99 Symphonies, tweak them, build my own, a=
nd backtest them all
It=E2=80=99s a much simpler way to build a balanced, diversified portfolio =
than I could on my own
If you=E2=80=99ve also realized you might not be as much of a trading geniu=
s as you thought last year=E2=80=A6=20
(1) TSMC Raises Arizona Chip Investment to $40 Billion as Biden Visits [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/f3a61ace-ca3e-4f49-b74d-f4461597410d?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Yang Jie [ https://substack.com/redirect/85994ab4-0ff8-43c0-85f3-b5119e524f=
de?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and=
 Ken Thomas [ https://substack.com/redirect/0dcc661e-c660-496c-a25a-1a0bd4c=
5db19?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =
for The Wall Street Journal
The second factory, first reported by The Wall Street Journal [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/f23c577b-6410-408b-af5d-8626b2a2bedd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], will make chips with 3-n=
anometer technology, equal to the tiniest and fastest chips available today=
, and TSMC=E2=80=99s total investment in Arizona will expand to $40 billion=
, the White House said. It didn=E2=80=99t say how many years the investment=
 would cover.
Earlier this week, President Biden visited the site of TSMC=E2=80=99s chip =
manufacturing facility in Arizona. This was on the heels of the White House=
 announcement that the Taiwanese chip manufacturer committed to opening a s=
econd factory on the site and to increasing its planned investment from $12=
B to $40B. It=E2=80=99s interesting that these announcements are coming fro=
m the White House and not TSMC itself =E2=80=94 the Biden Administration cl=
early views the re-shoring of chip manufacturing as a political priority, a=
nd has continued to double-down on it with both policy and PR. We tend to b=
elieve that the U.S. reducing its reliance on foreign manufacturing is a go=
od thing =E2=80=94 specifically when it comes to chips =E2=80=94 but we=E2=
=80=99d be remiss to not mention the challenges with this plan.=20
Ben Thompson has a good overview here [ https://substack.com/redirect/143fe=
ddd-5a4a-4d31-9051-e65ccfb6ebb2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], but in short, the TSMC chips in Arizona will cos=
t about 50% more, be a few years behind the chips being produced in Taiwan,=
 and do little to prevent a worst-case-scenario China invasion of Taiwan. T=
here are also apparently challenges in attracting the right talent to staff=
 these factories and relatively serious clashes in management styles betwee=
n TSMC and its American partners.
So perhaps this really is all a show of pomp and circumstance, and these tw=
o factories are really just two very expensive Biden monuments. Or, perhaps=
 more optimistically, this is a flawed but necessary first step in re-shori=
ng American manufacturing capabilities and trying to ensure that we don=E2=
=80=99t get caught flat-footed and chip-less.=20
(2) The brief history of artificial intelligence [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/67e9e187-a47b-42f5-bb27-edf8db5dac79?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Max Roser [ https://substack.com/redirect/e4700ac4-65a7-48fc-9484-4e6590344=
191?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] fo=
r Our World in Data
There=E2=80=99s a reason chips have become increasingly political =E2=80=94=
 they are super important, especially in rapidly growing field of AI. Our W=
orld in Data released a report that shows, quite clearly, that we are appro=
aching (or are already in) the golden age of AI. Slowly at first then all a=
t once =E2=80=94 as the OWID charts show, many of the AI developments we ar=
e seeing today are actually the result of multi-decade slogs in computing, =
chip design, and theory.
And it=E2=80=99s all starting to come together: in just the past 10 years, =
AI has started to outperform humans in handwriting recognition, speech reco=
gnition, image recognition, reading comprehension, and language understandi=
ng. And the slope of advancement is increasing =E2=80=94 it took AI 15 year=
s to outperform humans in handwriting recognition but only 1 year to outper=
form us in the more complex goal of language understanding.
Our World in Data does a great job charting out all of the data (and you sh=
ould check out the full report), but I think one Tim Urban graph captures a=
ll the AI developments even more succinctly:
(3) Precise atom manipulation through deep reinforcement learning [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/7b318245-72d2-42e6-a82d-127f5e246b9d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Chen, Aapro, Kipnis, Ilin, Liljeroth, and Foster in Nature via Eli Dourado =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/2e42d10f-e4e6-49e6-99f1-e74924e48ff5?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
The results demonstrate that state-of-the-art DRL can offer effective solut=
ions to real-world challenges in nanofabrication and powerful approaches to=
 increasingly complex scientific experiments at the atomic scale.
While most of the recent AI excitement has focused on the wild consumer-fac=
ing tech that we now have access to =E2=80=94 ChatGPT, Stable Difussion, an=
d the like =E2=80=94 AI=E2=80=99s impact is being felt in science and engin=
eering, too.=20
In this paper, the authors use deep reinforcement learning to  solve automa=
tion problems in nanofabrication, where =E2=80=9Cengineering quantum states=
 requires precise manipulations at the atomic level.=E2=80=9D=20
One of my favorite books of the year, as you=E2=80=99re probably sick of he=
aring, is Where Is My Flying Car? [ https://substack.com/redirect/63d34ee1-=
c9e4-4981-9b80-734f34106d2c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] When I saw Eli Dourado=E2=80=99s tweet about this Nat=
ure article, my ears perked up, and I went back to my WIMFC notes. There it=
 was:=20
The three major, interacting, and mutually accelerating technologies in the=
 21st century are likely to be nuclear, nanotech (biotech is the =E2=80=9Cl=
ow-pressure steam=E2=80=9D of nanotech), and AI, coming together in a syner=
gy that I have taken to calling the Second Atomic Age. It could easily impr=
ove productivity another couple orders of magnitude. It could almost certai=
nly lengthen our Lives beyond the antediluvian Standard. The science fictio=
n writers of the 1950s imagined mastering the solar system with a slightly =
advanced version of mature Industrial Revolution technology, but Second Ato=
mic Age technology is much more likely the level needed to make this master=
y feasible, viable, and sustainable.
If that=E2=80=99s the promise of nanotech x AI, this paper is a welcome ste=
p. I think it=E2=80=99s also just another hint that the future is going to =
be born from the intersections of all technologies we talk about here every=
 week.
(4) Here=E2=80=99s why we=E2=80=99re not prepared for the next wave of biot=
ech innovation [ https://substack.com/redirect/73a69861-d8fe-4aa7-943c-20eb=
e44f0f80?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ]
Matthew Herper [ https://substack.com/redirect/8a317f6b-2cb9-42e2-ae57-6d22=
f8c99fd7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ] for STAT
Here=E2=80=99s what =E2=80=9Cbiology=E2=80=99s century=E2=80=9D means to me=
: In the same way the 20th century belonged to physics, the 21st is biologi=
cal. But while physics in the 20th century brought airplanes, personal comp=
uters, and posters of Albert Einstein, it also meant the atom bomb and a co=
mplete transformation of the social order.
Now, we=E2=80=99re approaching a moment when changes in what we understand =
about biology are every bit as exhilarating and terrifying.
We=E2=80=99re big believers in The Century of Biology here at Not Boring =
=E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s even the name of Not Boring writer/investor Elliot H=
ershberg=E2=80=99s [ https://substack.com/redirect/ee8f070f-341c-422c-ba3a-=
2ed7c5ea4d29?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ] Substack, The Century of Biology [ https://substack.com/redirect/2f3=
ccc02-1560-453a-9f94-50399c272f72?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
Biology has made incredible advances in the past decade alone:
Genetically altered white blood cells [ https://substack.com/redirect/124cb=
c8c-6032-46e8-8b96-29a6fdf2aec5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that can cure cancer. A gene therapy [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/f94e986b-b3f6-4cd3-9e54-abb53c1399ab?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that gave sight to blind=
 children. Pills that wrench decades of life from a cancer death sentence o=
r ease the breathing of patients with cystic fibrosis [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/c6819136-464c-465e-9af5-508aeac6b33b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. And, of course, not one but seve=
ral effective Covid-19 vaccines created only a year into a once-in-a-centur=
y pandemic.
The science continues to progress, and seems to be moving even faster than =
it did in the past decade, in part due to biology=E2=80=99s intersection wi=
th AI. But Harper cautions that our infrastructure, specifically enrolling =
enough people in studies to make sure the drugs actually work, may continue=
 to be a big bottleneck.=20
We love us some innovation here at Not Boring, but this piece is a reminder=
 that the infrastructure is often just as important. The innovations don=E2=
=80=99t matter if they don=E2=80=99t get to market. Harper put it well:
The U.S. health care system tends to believe that inventing brand new gadge=
ts is the answer to everything. The result is that we try to solve problems=
 by building faster and more expensive Ferraris when what we really need ar=
e better roads.
(5) Scientists Eye Monoclonal Antibodies for Malaria as Drug Resistance Loo=
ms [ https://substack.com/redirect/ac496ab1-90cd-4cbe-a8c2-399153007073?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Madison Muller [ https://substack.com/redirect/3609c7ae-24eb-4f8f-933d-2f24=
49ddfa35?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ] for Bloomberg, h/t Alec Stapp [ https://substack.com/redirect/6e00c4af-7=
2c5-4011-ba4c-a5872f13a7b3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Soon, antibody drugs=C2=A0could also be used to prevent another disease: ma=
laria. Early study results showed that when administered=C2=A0intravenously=
, a high-dose of=C2=A0an=C2=A0antibody drug developed by scientists at the =
National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases was about 88% effecti=
ve [ https://substack.com/redirect/3fed0451-2143-4385-ade2-7e15d50a226f?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] at shie=
lding adults from=C2=A0infection in Mali over the 6-month malaria season.
A new monoclonal antibody drug, developed by the NIAID, was 88% effective a=
t preventing adults from malaria infection during a 6 month study period in=
 Mali. We wrote about the potential eradication of malaria in WDoO #15 [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/15c3781f-2c08-4e9d-b890-040981c06e9b?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and these result=
s indicate that we are well on our way. Beyond its effectiveness, the antib=
ody only has to be administered once per year, which means that distributio=
n and adherence may be more plausible in areas that are the hardest to reac=
h and hardest hit by malaria.
Go science.=20
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox 9am E=
ST on Monday morning. Enjoy the weekend!
